story.title: Falco - Episode 4
story.storyDescription: Libby Dixon is missing. Will Agent Falco crack the case?

messages.text: Investigation: Day 4
The following is an email exchange between Director Philomena Todd and Agent Falco.
The following is a transcript of an interview between Agent Falco, Deputy Decker, and Creed Keating, recorded June 23, 9:10 AM.
Good morning, Mr. Keating. Could you please state your full name and occupation for the record?
Creed Keating. I own the ice cream parlor on 6th and Main.
Scoops?
Yeah, Scoops.
So you’re Libby Dixon’s boss, correct?
Yeah. I called Lynette when Libby didn’t show up for her shift.
What was Libby like as an employee?
She was reliable, hard-working, kind of quiet.
Was it like her to call out of work or miss her shifts entirely?
No. She’s never even been late.
That’s why I was worried.
When’s the last time you saw her, Creed?
She worked the night before she disappeared. Clocked out around 6:30.
Did she seem upset or more preoccupied than usual?
Yeah, she was all teary-eyed—
Business was slow so I let her leave early.
Do you have any idea what she could’ve been upset about?
I kind of just assumed it was boy troubles or something.
What makes you think that, Mr. Keating?
Libby came to work with a black eye back in March.
I heard it had to do with her boyfriend.
That sounds like more than your run-of-the-mill “boy troubles” — doesn’t it?
Yeah, it does. She took a short sick leave after that—
I think she was in the psych ward or whatever.
But she seemed to bounce back okay.
Bounce back?
I thought she was doing better, yeah.
I heard she broke up with her boyfriend about a month ago, I guess.
Are you referring to Duke Simmons?
I’m not naming names, Agent.
This is a missing child, Mr. Keating.
I need names.
It’s okay, Creed. We know it was Duke.
Okay, yeah. I’m talking about Duke Simmons.
He kept on coming into Scoops to check up on her, all possessive-like.
When was the last time you saw Duke at Scoops?
About a month ago, I guess. I think that’s when she dumped him.
She could’ve been seeing someone new.
What makes you think so?
She seemed kind of different — lighter, I guess.
Like a teen in love, you know?
Do you know who she might have been seeing?
No clue, Agent. She was really private about stuff like that.
Probably didn’t want her dad to know about it.
What can you tell us about Darrence Dixon?
Typical overprotective father.
He’d call sometimes to check up on her—
Make sure she was on time, ask about her work ethic, or whatever.
It was a little much, to tell you the truth.
Libby even said her dad installed some kind of tracker on her computer, too.
Did she say anything else about her Internet use?
Well, I know she asked Carter how to delete the tracking software or whatever.
She deleted the tracking software?
I guess so. Carter’s our resident computer geek, so he probably knew how to do it.
Did Libby ever seem afraid of her father?
I don’t know. I think she just needed some room to breathe.
She complained about his rules a lot.
Rules?
Well, I know she’s not allowed to have a passcode on her phone.
And he took her bedroom door off its hinges.
Excuse me?
Both hers and Anna Mae’s, actually.
Libby said he doesn’t want them doing drugs or having sex, so he took the doors off to keep an eye on them.
So where do the girls change clothes?
I don’t know — the bathroom, I guess.
Anna Mae’s nineteen — why doesn’t she move out?
I doubt her father would pay for that.
She could get a job, couldn’t she?
She used to clerk at the Greenwald’s across the street, but she quit without notice at the beginning of June.
How do you know she quit her job?
Lee Greenwald’s a friend of the family.
He told me he was hurting for help—
Lost two clerks in two months before Anna Mae.
Do you know why she quit so suddenly?
No, but Lee said she was really emotional.
I heard she went through a bad breakup.
Do you know anything about that, Creed?
Wasn’t she with the mechanic — Jimmy Fitz?
I think so.
I hadn’t heard about their break-up.
Listen, I’ve had about enough teen gossip, thanks to my employees.
I can imagine.
Okay, is there anything else you think we should know about Libby, Mr. Keating?
I reckon not.
Then we’ll be in touch if we have any more questions, okay?
Thanks for coming in, Creed. I’ll swing by for some Rocky Road soon.
I’ll be expecting you, Tex.
The following is a voicemail from Agent Falco to Lynette Dixon, left June 23, 3:14 PM.
Mrs. Dixon, this is Agent Falco. I’d like to take a look at Libby’s computer, if that’s okay.
I know you said your husband installed a keystroke tracker on it, which could offer us some clues about Libby’s state of mind or personal contacts prior to her disappearance.
I hope you’re all holding up okay. Call me back when you can. Thanks so much. Bye.
The following is a text message conversation between Deputy Decker and Agent Falco, initiated June 23, 5:08 PM.
Okay, Agent, I went out to the Wired cafe like you asked. This place is a real dump.
Do they have security cameras?
Yeah, but they’re for “looks only.”
What the hell does that mean?
They aren’t functional.
They’re meant to scare people into behaving, I guess.
So that’s what we have to work with?
Is there some sort of sign-in sheet?
Negative.
But the clerk remembers a “troubled young woman” coming in about twice a week.
Does the clerk have the credit card receipt?
Nope.
She paid in cash.
Well, shit.
There’s some good news, too, though.
Oh, really?
I showed Libby’s missing poster to the clerk.
Yeah, and?
He said, and I quote — “Yeah, that’s the broad with the big boobs.”
It’s crude, but an ID, nonetheless.
Okay, wait—
Are you telling me that “Connor Mason” has been positively identified by the Wired clerk as Elizabeth Dixon?
Looks like it.
Holy hell.
Yeah. So what now, boss?
